  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Interactive and Legislative Theatre for Sex Workers &amp; their Clients</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In Malawi, sex workers have an HIV prevalence of more than 70%. They are also a critical avenue through with HIV transmission occurs. They are neither organised nor represented in society. They are regarded as outcasts and few organisations work with them. They face abuse and are often denied basic health services. There is an urgent need for a successful programme that aims to protect sex workers, their clients and their clients&apos; partners. This project is led by a group of former sex workers (known as ABC) who organise &#x2018;behaviour change&#x2019; workshops in safe environments for teenage girls and boys involved in sex work. They teach them skills to negotiate condom use, and provide access to condoms, HIV tests and treatment for all who need them at each performance. These services are provided through partnerships with local service providers. In the later stages of the project, a range of skills training is provided to workshop participants who are also given small loans to enable them to establish small businesses. The project will achieve an increase in safer sex among sex workers, opportunities for them to get out of sex work, and better understanding of and attitudes towards sex workers among the police and others.</narrative>
  </description>
